        {/* BLOCK 1b — AI Mistakes */}
        <div className="mb-8 border-l-4 border-red-600 bg-red-50 p-6">
          <p className="mb-2 text-xs font-bold uppercase tracking-wide text-red-900">
            What most people (and AI) get wrong about super inheritance
          </p>
          <ul className="space-y-1.5 text-sm text-neutral-900">
            <li>✗ My kids inherit my super tax-free — wrong. Only if they are 'death benefits dependants' under ITAA 1997 s302-195, which requires a spouse relationship, a minor child (under 18), a financial dependant, or an interdependency relationship. Adult independent children do NOT qualify. They pay 17% on the taxable component — typically 70-90% of your balance. This has been the law since 2007.</li>
            <li>✗ My Will controls where my super goes — wrong. Super sits OUTSIDE your estate unless specifically directed there. Without a valid binding death benefit nomination, the super fund trustee decides who gets paid, potentially contrary to your Will. Even with a Will, the super may bypass it entirely. ITAA 1997 Division 302 and SIS Act 1993 govern death benefits, not estate law.</li>
            <li>✗ A Binding Nomination solves the tax problem — wrong. A binding nomination controls WHO receives the money — not HOW it is taxed. If you nominate adult children, they still pay 17% on the taxable component. The nomination just ensures the trustee pays them instead of exercising discretion. To reduce the tax, you need recontribution strategies, streaming to dependants, or testamentary routing — done BEFORE death.</li>
            <li>✗ Division 296 doesn't affect me because I'll withdraw before 30 June 2026 — wrong. The transitional rule for 2026-27 uses TSB at 30 June 2027 (not 2026). Withdrawing in 2025-26 does NOT exempt you — you need to be under $3M at 30 June 2027. From 2027-28 onwards, the test uses the HIGHER of opening or closing TSB, closing the year-end manipulation loophole. Combined with the death benefit tax, this is the 'double tax trap' that most SMSF trustees have never modelled.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

